{"cursor":"29600","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Chembox\n| verifiedrevid = 477162765 ImageFile1 = SodiumHydroxide.jpg ImageFile1_Ref =\n| ImageName1 = Sample of sodium hydroxide as pellets in a watchglass ImageFile =\n| Sodium-hydroxide-crystal-3D-vdW.png ImageFile_Ref = ImageName = Unit cell,\n| spacefill model of sodium hydroxide PIN = Sodium hydroxide SystematicName = Sodium oxidanide OtherNames = Caustic\n| soda\nLye  Ascarite White caustic\nSodium hydrate\n\n| Section1 = {{Chembox Identifiers CASNo = 1310-73-2 CASNo_Ref = PubChem = 14798\n| PubChem_Ref = ChemSpiderID = 14114 ChemSpiderID_Ref = UNII = 55X04QC32I\n| UNII_Ref = EINECS = 215-185-5 UNNumber = 1823 KEGG = D01169 KEGG_Ref =\n| MeSHName = Sodium+Hydroxide ChEBI = 32145 ChEBI_Ref = RTECS = WB4900000 Gmelin\n| = 68430 SMILES = O[Na] StdInChI = 1S/Na.H2O/h;1H2/q+1;/p-1 StdInChI_Ref =\n| InChI = 1/Na.H2O/h;1H2/q+1;/p-1 StdInChIKey = HEMHJVSKTPXQMS-UHFFFAOYSA-M\n| StdInChIKey_Ref = InChIKey = HEMHJVSKTPXQMS-REWHXWOFAM\n}}\n| Section2 = {{Chembox Properties Formula = MolarMass = 39.9971 g mol -\n| 1 ExactMass = 39.992509329 g mol â1 Appearance = White, waxy,\n| opaque crystals Odor = odorless Density = 2.13 g/cm 3 MeltingPtC =\n| 318 BoilingPtC = 1388 Solubility = 111 g/100 mL (at 20 Â°C) Solvent1 = methanol\n| Solubility1 = 23.8 g/100 mL Solvent2 = ethanol Solubility2 = â1 Entropy =\n| 64 JÂ·mol â1 Â·K â1\n }}\n| Section4 = {{Chembox Hazards ExternalMSDS = [http://www.certified-lye.com/MSDS-\n| Lye.pdf External MSDS] GHSPictograms = EUIndex = 011-002-00-6 EUClass =\n| RPhrases = SPhrases = , , , NFPA-H = 3 NFPA-F = 0 NFPA-R = 1 NFPA-O = ALK\n}}\n| Section5 = {{Chembox Related OtherAnions = Sodium hydrosulfide OtherCations =\n| Caesium hydroxide\nLithium hydroxide Potassium hydroxide Rubidium hydroxide }} }}\n\n'Sodium hydroxide', also known as '[[lye]]' or 'caustic soda', has the molecular formula\n'[[Sodium|Na]][[Hydroxide|OH]]' and is a highly caustic metallic base. It\nis a white solid available in pellets, flakes, granules, and as a 50%\nsaturated solution.\n\nSodium hydroxide is soluble in water, ethanol and methanol. This alkali is\ndeliquescent and readily absorbs moisture and carbon dioxide in air.\n\nSodium hydroxide is used in many industries, mostly as a strong chemical base in\nthe manufacture of pulp and paper, textiles, drinking water, soaps and\ndetergents and as a drain cleaner. Worldwide production in 2004 was\napproximately 60 million tonnes, while demand was 51 million\ntonnes. Although molten sodium hydroxide possesses\nproperties similar to those of the other forms, its high temperature\ncomparatively limits its applications.\n","linknr":700,"url":"Sodium_Hydroxide","recorded":1362482472,"links":98,"instances":["chemistry","substance","biology","chemistry","molecule","chemistry","chemistry","lubricant","chemistry"],"pdf":["http://www.certified-lye.com/MSDS-Lye.pdf","http://www.certified-lye.com/MSDS-Lye.pdf","http://www.certified-lye.com/MSDS-Lye.pdf","http://www.hillbrothers.com/msds/pdf/sodium-hydroxide-10-50-liq.pdf","http://www.hillbrothers.com/msds/pdf/sodium-hydroxide-10-50-liq.pdf","http://fss.k-state.edu/FeaturedContent/CarcassDisposal/PDF%20Files/CH%206%20-%20Alkaline%20Hydrolysis.pdf","http://ucanr.org/freepubs/docs/8267.pdf","http://ucanr.org/freepubs/docs/8267.pdf","http://www1.eere.energy.gov/hydrogenandfuelcells/pdfs/aluminium_water_hydrogen.pdf","http://www1.eere.energy.gov/hydrogenandfuelcells/pdfs/aluminium_water_hydrogen.pdf","http://ecb.jrc.ec.europa.eu/DOCUMENTS/Existing-Chemicals/RISK_ASSESSMENT/REPORT/sodiumhydroxidereport416.pdf"],"categories":["Chemical engineering","Cleaning products","Household chemicals","Sodium compounds","Inorganic compounds","Hydroxides","Deliquescent substances","Desiccants","Photographic chemicals"],"headings":["Properties","Production","Uses","Safety","See also","References","Bibliography","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/6/63